git clone git@github.com:USER-NAME/REPOSITORY-NAME.git or git clone https://github.com/user-name/repository-name.git

git push origin master

git add .

git commit -m "A message describing what you have done to make this snapshot different"

git status
git log

The basic Git syntax is program | action | destination.

git add . is read as git | add | ., where the period represents everything in the current directory;

git commit -m "message" is read as git | commit -m | "message"; and

git status is read as git | status | (no destination).

Git init = creates a local repository

git clone /path/to/repository = creates a working copy from a local repository

git clone username@host:/path/to/repository = creates a copy from a remote server

git add <filename> = adds file to staging area
git add . = adds all files to staging area

git commit = commits the staging area to the live version

git push origin master = pushes live version to online repository

git status = shows you what files are in staging and what is to be added

git pull = pulls from the online repository

git merge <branchname> = merges branch into your active branch

git checkout -- <filename> = does something